This was reported against v4.140.2, which explicitly rejected directory paths. The VSCode extension has migrated to v7.x which resolves this, but the JetBrains plugin remains affected.

## What the old code did

In v4.x/v5.x, `ReadFileTool` rejected directories outright:

```ts
// v5.x — src/core/tools/ReadFileTool.ts
if (stats.isDirectory()) {
  const errorMsg = `Cannot read '${relPath}' because it is a directory. ` +
    `To view the contents of a directory, use the list_files tool instead.`
```

This created a common failure pattern: the LLM calls `read_file` on a directory path, gets an error, and either retries with the same path or switches to a different (often wrong) approach. As noted in the report, this hit many models — Qwen, GLM, Kimi, and others.

## v7.x supports directories in the read tool

Commit [`6b4d617`](https://github.com/Kilo-Org/kilocode/commit/6b4d617df0) (#13090) added native directory support:

```ts
// v7.x — packages/opencode/src/tool/read.ts
if (stat.isDirectory()) {
  const dirents = await fs.readdir(filepath, { withFileTypes: true })
  const entries = await Promise.all(
    dirents.map(async (dirent) => {
      if (dirent.isDirectory()) return dirent.name + "/"
      // ...
    })
  )
  entries.sort((a, b) => a.localeCompare(b))
  // Returns formatted directory listing with pagination
}
```

Instead of erroring, the tool now lists directory entries with trailing `/` for subdirectories, supports `offset`/`limit` pagination, and shows total entry count. No prompt modification needed — it just works.

## Platform status

| Platform | Latest version | Architecture | Bug status |
|----------|---------------|-------------|------------|
| VSCode | v7.0.33 | New (`packages/opencode/`) | Resolved |
| GoLand / IntelliJ / etc. | v5.9.0 | Old (`src/core/tools/`) | **Still affected** |

The old VSCode extension source now lives in [Kilo-Org/kilocode-legacy](https://github.com/Kilo-Org/kilocode-legacy), which is no longer actively maintained. VSCode users on v5.9.0 should auto-update to v7.x.

The [JetBrains plugin](https://plugins.jetbrains.com/plugin/28350-kilo-code) is still on v5.9.0 and bundles the old `extension.js` containing `ReadFileTool`. v7.x does not ship a JetBrains artifact, so this bug remains live for all JetBrains IDE users.

