### Description

One of the main problems with the Kilo plugin is its lack of proper support for right-to-left (RTL) languages such as Persian, Arabic, and Hebrew. When a user interacts with the plugin in Persian (or any other RTL language), all texts, responses, buttons, and user interface elements are displayed in left-to-right (LTR) direction. This causes:

- Persian texts to appear reversed and incomplete (e.g., letters disconnected and without proper joining).
- Reading responses and messages to become extremely difficult, sometimes impossible.
- A severely disrupted user experience for millions of people who use RTL languages.

This issue affects not only Persian-speaking users but also all users of Arabic, Hebrew, Urdu, and other RTL languages. It can be a significant barrier to wider adoption of the plugin in the Middle East and Islamic countries.

### Why Fixing This Issue Is Simple

Supporting RTL in modern web development is highly standardized and straightforward. It only requires a few small changes to the plugin's CSS and HTML:

1. **Automatic text direction detection**: Adding the `dir="auto"` attribute to main elements (such as divs containing text) allows the browser to automatically detect the text direction based on the content language.
2. **Setting overall interface direction**: Adding an `rtl` class to the page body when the user's language is RTL, along with corresponding CSS rules.
3. **RTL-specific styles**: Writing CSS rules for RTL mode (e.g., margins, padding, alignment, and icon positioning).

### Proposed Solution (with Code Examples)

For a quick and effective implementation, you can use the following approach:

#### 1. Detect User Language and Apply dir
In the main `<html>` tag or plugin body:

```html
<html dir="auto" lang="{{user_language}}">
```

Or dynamically with JavaScript:

```javascript
if (['fa', 'ar', 'he', 'ur'].includes(userLanguage)) {
    document.documentElement.dir = 'rtl';
    document.body.classList.add('rtl');
}
```

#### 2. Basic CSS Styles for RTL

```css
body.rtl {
    direction: rtl;
    text-align: right;
}

body.rtl .message-container {
    direction: rtl;
}

body.rtl .input-box {
    text-align: right;
    padding-right: 12px; /* instead of padding-left */
}

body.rtl .button-icon {
    margin-left: 8px; /* reversed to margin-right */
    margin-right: 0;
}

/* To flip icons in RTL mode */
body.rtl .icon-arrow-left {
    transform: scaleX(-1);
}
```

#### 3. Use dir="auto" for User and Assistant Texts

```html
<div class="message user-message" dir="auto">
    {{user_input}}
</div>

<div class="message assistant-message" dir="auto">
    {{assistant_response}}
</div>
```

With these simple changes (fewer than 50 lines of CSS and a few lines of JavaScript), the Kilo plugin will become fully compatible with RTL languages, and Persian texts will be displayed correctly and beautifully.

### Conclusion

Fixing RTL support is not just a minor technical improvement—it is an important step toward accessibility and inclusivity. This change can dramatically enhance the experience for millions of users in Persian-speaking, Arabic-speaking, and other RTL regions, while increasing user satisfaction and loyalty.

It is recommended that this feature be prioritized in the next plugin updates.

